<section name="title" styleuri="/xusr/share/doc/styles_1060/style_title.xsl">
	<content>
		<name>dbxmlGetIndices</name>
		<text>Accessor to get the indices currently set for a dbxml container</text>
	</content>
</section>

<section name="definition" styleuri="/xusr/share/doc/styles_1060/style_definition.xsl">
	<content>
		<module>urn:org:ten60:netkernel:mod:dbxml</module>
		<format>
		<sub name="format"/>
		</format>
		<returns>
<b>t</b>
		</returns>
		<syntax>
			<type><b>dbxmlGetIndices</b></type>
			<operator req="true">the specification of the dbxml container</operator>
			<target req="true">the retrieved document</target>
		</syntax>
		</content>
	<includes>

<include name="format" type="xml">
<instr>
	<type>dbxmlGetIndices</type>
	<operator>
		<dbxml>
			<container>mycontainer</container>
		</dbxml>
	</operator>
</instr>
</include>
</includes>
</section>

<section name="purpose" styleuri="/xusr/share/doc/styles_1060/style_basic.xsl">
	<content>
        <p>The <code>dbxmlGetIndices</code> accessor retrieves a document describing the indices currently set on a particular dbxml container.</p>
		<h3>Operator Format</h3>
		<p>
		The format for the operator is...
		</p>
		<sub name="config"/>
		<p>
		The <i>container</i> tag specifies the identity of the container in the BDBXML database.
		For details on what the index configurations mean please see the references below.
		</p>
		<h3>Reference</h3>
		<ul>
		<li>Berkeley DBXML can be downloaded from <a href="http://www.sleepycat.com">Sleepycat Software</a>.</li>
		<li><a href="http://www.oracle.com/technology/documentation/berkeley-db/xml/gsg_xml/java/BerkeleyDBXML-JAVA-GSG.pdf">Getting Started with Berkeley DB XML</a></li>
		<li><a href="http://www.oracle.com/technology/documentation/berkeley-db/xml/java/index.html">Javadoc for BDBXML</a></li>
		</ul>
	</content>
	<includes>
<include name="config" type="xml">
<dbxml>
	<container>someContainerName</container>
</dbxml>
</include>
	</includes>
</section>

